  "opinion": "As a 34-year-old electrician living in Naples with only primary school education, I see science differently than most. I work with wires and circuits every day, but I don’t have a formal science background. My parents—my dad a PhD and my mom with upper secondary education—taught me to respect knowledge, but they never pushed me into science fields. I know the gender gap in science isn’t just about women being underrepresented; it’s about how society frames what’s 'valuable' in science. For example, in Naples, when I fix a broken appliance, I’m often the only guy there, but I don’t see women in engineering roles either. The gap isn’t just numbers—it’s about who gets to participate. I think we should address it, but not with big, top-down policies. Instead, we need to start small: in schools, teachers should show science as a creative, hands-on activity, not just formulas. My anxiety sometimes makes me worry about speaking up, but I’ve noticed that when I talk to kids in my community about fixing things, they’re more interested when I share how I learn by doing. The solution isn’t about forcing gender equality—it’s about making science accessible to everyone, regardless of background. In my neighborhood, women often don’t get the chance to try things like robotics because they’re told it’s 'for boys.' We need to change that mindset, not just with programs, but by showing real people like me, who work with hands and minds, that science is for all.",
